Minerals

  • Definition:
    • Naturally occurring, inorganic solids with a definite chemical composition and crystal structure.
    • Examples: Quartz, Feldspar, Mica.
  • Characteristics:
    • Chemical Composition: Fixed chemical formula (e.g., NaCl for Halite).
    • Crystal Structure: Regular, repeating arrangement of atoms.
    • Formation: Typically formed through geological processes like crystallization from magma or precipitation from solutions.

Rocks:

  • Definition:
    • Solid aggregates composed of (one or more) minerals.
    • Examples: Granite (composed of Quartz, Feldspar, and Mica), Limestone (composed of Calcite).
  • Characteristics:
    • Composition: Can include a mixture of minerals and/or mineraloids.
    • Texture: Varies based on mineral composition, grain size, and formation process.
    • Formation: Formed through various geological processes such as cooling and solidification of magma (igneous rocks), compression and cementation of sediments (sedimentary rocks), or alteration of existing rocks (metamorphic rocks).

Rocks vs.Â Minerals

  • Composition:
    • Minerals: Single substance with a specific chemical composition.
    • Rocks: Mixture of multiple minerals or mineraloids.
  • Structure:
    • Minerals: Defined crystal structure.
    • Rocks: Aggregates of minerals with varying structures.
  • Formation:
    • Minerals: Crystallize from molten material, form through evaporation, or precipitate from aqueous solutions.
    • Rocks: Formed through geological processes involving minerals or organic matter.

The Rock Cycle and Involved Processes

The Rock Cycle, Source: Steven, E. (2015)

Summary

  • Rock Types Produced Through the Cycle:
    • Igneous Rocks: Formed from the solidification of molten magma or lava (e.g., basalt, granite).
    • Sedimentary Rocks: Formed from the accumulation and compaction of sediments (e.g., sandstone, limestone).
    • Metamorphic Rocks: Formed from the transformation of existing rocks due to heat, pressure, or chemically active fluids (e.g., marble, schist).
  • Processes That Change Rocks From Form to Form:
    • Cooling and Solidification: Magma cools and solidifies to form igneous rocks.
    • Weathering and Erosion: Igneous and metamorphic rocks break down into sediments.
    • Compaction and Cementation: Sediments compact and cement together to form sedimentary rocks.
    • Metamorphism: Sedimentary and igneous rocks undergo heat and pressure to become metamorphic rocks.
    • Melting: Metamorphic and sedimentary rocks melt into magma, starting the cycle again.
